On Dr. Tufte’s Remarks
Get the insight right, and search for excellent ways to do so - these things should be done and are hard to do so. Or, as data scientist Ella Hilal denotes - outcomes over output. This would appear to have been the central insight offered by Dr. Tufte back during his keynote address for Microsoft’s 2016 Machine Learning & Data Science Summit.
Considered by many in the analysis industry as the ‘Galileo of graphics’, Tufte frequency draws lessons and inspirations from his adopted namesake in truth assaying. Such as the fact that information presented in a manner clearly amenable to interpretation by the mind’s very visual mode of orientation is the best way to get it to comprehend a topic or idea. Just as Galileo himself recommended that visual evidence, not untested conjecture alone, was the best standard with which to weigh metaphysical claims about the nature of the universe we inhibit.



An example of visual insight from another famous scientist. This time the jottings of Charles Darwin, outlining of an initial idea of natural selection. Note the “I think” at the top of the page. From the American Museum of Natural History.


He also proffers advice on salient aspects of the application of statistical methods to understanding truth via data. He cautions that we may in fact focus on traditional assertations of errors that are due to randomness simply because that aspect of analysis design is the most open to mathematical exposition (and manipulation). While other issues, such a researcher biases, framework deficiencies, etc. may be as much if not more important potential compromisers of our ability to draw truthful conclusions from data.
He also urges that the research community embrace attempts to validate and confirm the results of analysis, most poignantly with preregistration of study designs. Elsewise (to paraphrase slightly), we may not really be discovering truth, but simply what we ourselves want, or need, it to be.


Something a Little Different…
Creating a ‘Strange Chaotic Attractor’ via the methodology spelled out courtesy of Antonio Sánchez:


See:
https://codingclubuc3m.rbind.io/post/2019-10-15/
{r}
library(Rcpp)
library(tidyverse)
library(ggplot2)

cppFunction('DataFrame createTrajectory(int n, double x0, double y0,
            double a, double b, double c, double d) {
            NumericVector x(n);
            NumericVector y(n);
            x[0]=x0;
            y[0]=y0;
            for(int i = 1; i &lt; n; ++i) {
            x[i] = sin(a*y[i-1])+c*cos(a*x[i-1]);
            y[i] = sin(b*x[i-1])+d*cos(b*y[i-1]);
            }
            return DataFrame::create(_["x"]= x, _["y"]= y);
            }
            ')
a &lt;- -1.314159
b &lt;- -1.618033988
c &lt;- -1.271828
d &lt;- -1.11000100

frame &lt;- createTrajectory(10000000, 0, 0, a, b, c, d)
head(frame)
